Revisiting the Index Construction of Proximity Graph-Based Approximate Nearest Neighbor Search

Shuo Yang¬ß Xidian University yangsh@stu.xidian.edu.cn ,¬† Jiadong Xie¬ß The Chinese University of Hong Kong jdxie@se.cuhk.edu.hk ,¬† Yingfan Liu‚àó Xidian University liuyingfan@xidian.edu.cn ,¬† Jeffrey Xu Yu The Chinese University of Hong Kong yu@se.cuhk.edu.hk ,¬† Xiyue Gao Xidian University xygao@xidian.edu.cn ,¬† Qianru Wang Xidian University wangqianru@xidian.edu.cn ,¬† Yanguo Peng Xidian University ygpeng@xidian.edu.cn ¬†and¬† Jiangtao Cui Xidian University cuijt@xidian.edu.cn
Abstract.

Proximity graphs (PG) have gained increasing popularity as the state-of-the-art (SOTA) solutions to kùëòkitalic_k-approximate nearest neighbor (kùëòkitalic_k-ANN) search on high-dimensional data, which serves as a fundamental function in various fields, e.g. information retrieval and retrieval-augmented generation¬†(RAG). Although PG-based approaches have the best kùëòkitalic_k-ANN search performance, their index construction cost is superlinear to the number of points, since they have to identify close neighbors for each point to establish the edges. Such superlinear cost substantially limits their scalability in the era of big data. Hence, the goal of this paper is to accelerate the construction of PG-based methods without compromising their kùëòkitalic_k-ANN search performance.

To achieve this goal, two mainstream categories of PG are revisited: relative neighborhood graph (RNG) and navigable small world graph (NSWG). By revisiting their construction process, we find the issues of construction efficiency. To address these issues, we propose a new construction framework with a novel pruning strategy for edge selection, which accelerates RNG construction while keeping its kùëòkitalic_k-ANN search performance. Then, we integrate this framework into NSWG construction to enhance both the construction efficiency and kùëòkitalic_k-ANN search performance. Moreover, extensive experiments are conducted to validate our construction framework for both RNG and NSWG. The results demonstrate that it significantly reduces the PG construction cost, achieving up to 5.6x speedup while not compromising the kùëòkitalic_k-ANN search performance.

1. Introduction

Recent breakthroughs in deep learning models, specifically embedding models, have revolutionized the representation of various types of data, such as images and text chunks. These models transform the data into vectors, which encapsulate key information in a high-dimensional space for semantic analysis. As a result, kùëòkitalic_k-approximate nearest neighbor (kùëòkitalic_k-ANN) search on high-dimensional vectors has emerged as a fundamental problem across multiple domains, including information retrieval¬†(Grbovic and Cheng, 2018; Huang et¬†al., [n.‚Äâd.]), recommendation system¬†(Okura et¬†al., 2017) and large language models¬†(Barthel et¬†al., 2019; Lewis et¬†al., 2020; Guu et¬†al., 2020; Asai et¬†al., 2023; Liu et¬†al., 2024b). In particular, due to the popularity of retrieval-augmented generation¬†(RAG) (Lewis et¬†al., 2020; Asai et¬†al., 2023), kùëòkitalic_k-ANN search on high-dimensional vectors causes more and more attention as a key RAG component. Given a dataset D‚äÇ‚Ñùdùê∑superscript‚ÑùùëëD\subset\mathbb{R}^{d}italic_D ‚äÇ blackboard_R start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_d end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT and a query vector q‚àà‚Ñùdùëûsuperscript‚Ñùùëëq\in\mathbb{R}^{d}italic_q ‚àà blackboard_R start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_d end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT, kùëòkitalic_k-ANN search returns the kùëòkitalic_k vectors in Dùê∑Ditalic_D that are sufficiently close to qùëûqitalic_q, where kùëòkitalic_k is a specified parameter.

kùëòkitalic_k-ANN search has been extensively studied for several decades, hence there exists a wealth of methods in the literature¬†(Li et¬†al., 2019; Wang et¬†al., 2021a, 2017; Malkov et¬†al., 2014; Chen et¬†al., 2009; Tao et¬†al., 2009; Gan et¬†al., 2012; Liu et¬†al., 2014). According to recent studies¬†(Aum√ºller et¬†al., 2020; Li et¬†al., 2020, 2019; Wang et¬†al., 2021a), the proximity graph (PG) based methods (Chen et¬†al., 2009; Dong et¬†al., 2011; Malkov et¬†al., 2014; Malkov and Yashunin, 2018; Li et¬†al., 2019; Fu et¬†al., 2019, 2022; Peng et¬†al., 2023) have emerged as the promising solution and have demonstrated superior performance compared to other approaches, such as hashing-based methods (Lv et¬†al., 2007; Tao et¬†al., 2009; Gan et¬†al., 2012; Liu et¬†al., 2014; Sun et¬†al., 2015; Huang et¬†al., 2016), invert index-based methods (Jegou et¬†al., 2011; Babenko and Lempitsky, 2014) and tree-based methods (Bentley, 1975; Berchtold et¬†al., 1996; Katayama and Satoh, 1997; Muja and Lowe, 2014). A PG treats each vector u‚ààDùë¢ùê∑u\in Ditalic_u ‚àà italic_D as a graph vertex and then connects edges between uùë¢uitalic_u and its close neighbors. Notably, all PGs share the same vertex set but have various edge sets due to their distinct edge-selection strategies. According to previous studies¬†(Peng et¬†al., 2023; Wang et¬†al., 2021a; Li et¬†al., 2019; Pan et¬†al., 2024), PGs are divided into three categories by different neighbor-selection strategies: kùëòkitalic_k nearest neighbor graph (KNNG), relative neighborhood graph (RNG), and navigable small world graph (NSWG).

Although PG-based approaches have superior search performance, they still suffer from a significantly higher cost in terms of index construction than other methods. This is primarily due to the necessity of identifying close neighbors for each point to establish the graph edges. In the traditional applications of kùëòkitalic_k-ANN search, PG index is built offline and then responds to kùëòkitalic_k-ANN queries. Thus its construction cost is treated as a second-class performance indicator. However, in the emerging scenario, i.e., the RAG model training¬†(Guu et¬†al., 2020; Izacard et¬†al., 2023; Asai et¬†al., 2023), the PG index will be frequently built in an online manner, due to the tuning on the embedding model that transforms the source data such as text chunks into vectors. As a result, it is urgent to build PG efficiently while maintaining search performance. To address this issue, several studies have been proposed to accelerate the index construction, such as DiskANN¬†(Subramanya et¬†al., 2019), RNN-Descent¬†(Ono and Matsui, 2023), LSH-APG¬†(Zhao et¬†al., 2023) and ParlayANN¬†(Manohar et¬†al., 2024). However, as shown in Table¬†1, their search performance remains noticeably inferior to NSG¬†(Fu et¬†al., 2019), where NSG is one of SOTA methods that do not prioritize index construction. Hence, they sacrifice the search performance to expedite the index construction, which violates the primary goal of kùëòkitalic_k-ANN search.

In this work, we begin by revisiting the construction process of SOTA PGs, namely RNG and NSWG. On top of the KNNG, RNG is built with three key phases. According to recent studies¬†(Aum√ºller et¬†al., 2020; Li et¬†al., 2020, 2019; Wang et¬†al., 2021a), proximity graph (PG) based approaches are the SOTA methods for kùëòkitalic_k-ANN search. 2.1. Proximity Graph

A PG G=(V,E)ùê∫ùëâùê∏G=(V,E)italic_G = ( italic_V , italic_E ) of Dùê∑Ditalic_D is a directed graph, where each node in VùëâVitalic_V uniquely represents a vector (i.e., data point) in Dùê∑Ditalic_D, and two nodes are connected by an edge in Eùê∏Eitalic_E if their corresponding vectors are close to each other. For a node u‚ààVùë¢ùëâu\in Vitalic_u ‚àà italic_V, we use NG‚Å¢(u)subscriptùëÅùê∫ùë¢N_{G}(u)italic_N start_POSTSUBSCRIPT italic_G end_POSTSUBSCRIPT ( italic_u ) to denote the set of out-neighbors of node uùë¢uitalic_u in a PG Gùê∫Gitalic_G.

As presented in previous studies¬†(Peng et¬†al., 2023; Wang et¬†al., 2021a; Li et¬†al., 2019; Pan et¬†al., 2024), PGs are classified into three categories according to their edge-selection strategies.

kùëòkitalic_k-Nearest Neighbor Graph (KNNG): Each node in KNNG is connected to its kùëòkitalic_k-approximate nearest data points, which is proposed as an approximation of the Delaunay graph (DG)¬†(Aurenhammer, 1991), since DG becomes a complete graph when the dimension is large¬†(Harwood and Drummond, 2016; Peng et¬†al., 2023).

Relative Neighborhood Graph (RNG): RNG is constructed based on KNNG, it removes the longest edge in every possible triangle in the KNNG, i.e., if edge (u,v)ùë¢ùë£(u,v)( italic_u , italic_v ) exists in RNG, there exists no edge (u,w)ùë¢ùë§(u,w)( italic_u , italic_w ) in the graph such that d‚Å¢i‚Å¢s‚Å¢t‚Å¢(u,w)<d‚Å¢i‚Å¢s‚Å¢t‚Å¢(u,v)ùëëùëñùë†ùë°ùë¢ùë§ùëëùëñùë†ùë°ùë¢ùë£dist(u,w)<dist(u,v)italic_d italic_i italic_s italic_t ( italic_u , italic_w ) < italic_d italic_i italic_s italic_t ( italic_u , italic_v ) and d‚Å¢i‚Å¢s‚Å¢t‚Å¢(v,w)<d‚Å¢i‚Å¢s‚Å¢t‚Å¢(u,v)ùëëùëñùë†ùë°ùë£ùë§ùëëùëñùë†ùë°ùë¢ùë£dist(v,w)<dist(u,v)italic_d italic_i italic_s italic_t ( italic_v , italic_w ) < italic_d italic_i italic_s italic_t ( italic_u , italic_v ). RNG enhances its connectivity by adding extra edges between connected components, while limiting the out-degree of each node to a small constant¬†(Fu et¬†al., 2019).

Navigable Small World Graph (NSWG): NSWG is derived from Milgram‚Äôs social experiment¬†(Travers and Milgram, 1977), which demonstrates that two nodes in a large graph are connected by a short path that can be discovered through greedy routing. Hence, the NSWG construction involves incrementally node-by-node insertion, where each node is connected to its kùëòkitalic_k-ANN in the current incomplete graph.

2.2. Beam Search

Although PGs have different construction algorithms, they share the same search method called beam search, which is on top of greedy routing. Greedy routing involves selecting the nearest out-neighbor of the current node at each step and terminates when no closer out-neighbors are available.

To extend the greedy routing for kùëòkitalic_k-ANN search, beam search (i.e., the best-first search) is thus proposed. 3. PG Construction Revisited

In this section, we revisit the index construction of the SOTA PG approaches, namely RNG methods¬†(Fu et¬†al., 2019, 2022; Peng et¬†al., 2023; Subramanya et¬†al., 2019) and NSWG methods¬†(Malkov and Yashunin, 2018; Malkov et¬†al., 2014; Zhao et¬†al., 2023). We first present the construction process of RNG and NSWG respectively, followed by identifying their issues in building efficiency.

3.1. RNG Index Construction

To construct an RNG index, the computation of distances between each pair of nodes is necessary in order to eliminate the longest edge in all possible triangles. Unfortunately, its time complexity is O‚Å¢(n2‚Å¢d)ùëÇsuperscriptùëõ2ùëëO(n^{2}d)italic_O ( italic_n start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT 2 end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT italic_d ), which is practically impossible for large data. Hence, some studies propose to construct a practical version of RNG via another PG, such as KNNG¬†(Fu et¬†al., 2019, 2022), NSG¬†(Peng et¬†al., 2023) or even a random graph¬†(Subramanya et¬†al., 2019).

In this section, we take NSG as an RNG representative to discuss the construction process. This is because NSG is widely acknowledged as one of the SOTA methods for kùëòkitalic_k-ANN search¬†(Peng et¬†al., 2023; Wang et¬†al., 2021a), and recent studies focus on improving search performance by making minor modifications on NSG, e.g., extending the pruning strategy¬†(Fu et¬†al., 2022; Peng et¬†al., 2023).

3.2. NSWG Index Construction

Unlike RNG, NSWG is constructed by incrementally inserting nodes into the current graph and connecting each node to a subset of its kùëòkitalic_k-ANN found in the current graph. Following this idea, several methods such as NSW¬†(Malkov et¬†al., 2014), HNSW¬†(Malkov and Yashunin, 2018) and LSH-APG¬†(Zhao et¬†al., 2023) are proposed, where HNSW¬†(Malkov and Yashunin, 2018) stands out as the SOTA approach. Hence, in this section, we focus on the HNSW construction process.

3.3. PG Construction Issues

As discussed above, we can see that both RNG and NSWG construction share the same procedure for each node u‚ààDùë¢ùê∑u\in Ditalic_u ‚àà italic_D, i.e., finding a set of kùëòkitalic_k close neighbors of uùë¢uitalic_u, denoted size-kùëòkitalic_k candidate neighbor set acquisition (kùëòkitalic_k-CNA), and then derive the PG by the ùóãùñæùñøùóÇùóáùñæùóÜùñæùóáùóçùóãùñæùñøùóÇùóáùñæùóÜùñæùóáùóç\mathsf{refinement}sansserif_refinement phase that takes the kùëòkitalic_k-CNA results as input. Specifically, the RNG construction method combines ùóÇùóáùóÇùóçùóÇùñ∫ùóÖùóÇùóìùñ∫ùóçùóÇùóàùóáùóÇùóáùóÇùóçùóÇùñ∫ùóÖùóÇùóìùñ∫ùóçùóÇùóàùóá\mathsf{initialization}sansserif_initialization phase and ùóåùñæùñ∫ùóãùñºùóÅùóåùñæùñ∫ùóãùñºùóÅ\mathsf{search}sansserif_search phase to generate the kùëòkitalic_k-CNA results, while the ùóåùñæùñ∫ùóãùñºùóÅùóåùñæùñ∫ùóãùñºùóÅ\mathsf{search}sansserif_search phase of NSWG construction performs kùëòkitalic_k-ANN search on the current incomplete graph index for kùëòkitalic_k-CNA results. Hence, both RNG and NSWG are derived from the kùëòkitalic_k-CNA results in ùóãùñæùñøùóÇùóáùñæùóÜùñæùóáùóçùóãùñæùñøùóÇùóáùñæùóÜùñæùóáùóç\mathsf{refinement}sansserif_refinement phase.

Due to the importance of the kùëòkitalic_k-CNA results, there are two performance aspects of obtaining kùëòkitalic_k-CNA, i.e., efficiency and quality. First, the cost of obtaining kùëòkitalic_k-CNA results contributes to the total construction cost and thus its efficiency is key to the construction efficiency. Second, the kùëòkitalic_k-CNA quality, measured by the average over the recall of the kùëòkitalic_k-CNA neighbors for each node u‚ààDùë¢ùê∑u\in Ditalic_u ‚àà italic_D w.r.t. its exact kùëòkitalic_k nearest neighbors, significantly affects the kùëòkitalic_k-ANN search performance of the graph index derived from kùëòkitalic_k-CNA results. We present such an effect through the following experimental study.

The Importance of kùëòkitalic_k-CNA Quality: For the PG derived from kùëòkitalic_k-CNA results by ùóãùñæùñøùóÇùóáùñæùóÜùñæùóáùóçùóãùñæùñøùóÇùóáùñæùóÜùñæùóáùóç\mathsf{refinement}sansserif_refinement phase, there are two aspects of its search performance, i.e., efficiency by queries per second (QPS) and accuracy by R‚Å¢e‚Å¢c‚Å¢a‚Å¢l‚Å¢l‚Å¢@‚Å¢10ùëÖùëíùëêùëéùëôùëô@10Recall@10italic_R italic_e italic_c italic_a italic_l italic_l @ 10 of returned kùëòkitalic_k-ANN. As depicted in Figure¬†2, each curve represents the search performance of a derived PG with a distinct recall of kùëòkitalic_k-CNA results. The results clearly indicate that the kùëòkitalic_k-CNA quality significantly impacts the search performance of the derived PG. Specifically, the recall of kùëòkitalic_k-CNA results exhibits a positive effect on the search performance of PG. Such an effect could also observed on other PGs such as DPG and œÑùúè\tauitalic_œÑ-MNG. Notably, the kùëòkitalic_k-CNA quality of HNSW is limited to 0.5 due to its incremental node-by-node insertion strategy of index construction.

Considering the strong relationship between the quality of kùëòkitalic_k-CNA and search performance, we identify two issues in the construction of RNG and NSWG respectively.

RNG Construction Issue: RNG methods suffer from inefficiency in obtaining kùëòkitalic_k-CNA results, caused by ùóåùñæùñ∫ùóãùñºùóÅùóåùñæùñ∫ùóãùñºùóÅ\mathsf{search}sansserif_search phase that takes the initial KNNG generated by ùóÇùóáùóÇùóçùóÇùñ∫ùóÖùóÇùóìùñ∫ùóçùóÇùóàùóáùóÇùóáùóÇùóçùóÇùñ∫ùóÖùóÇùóìùñ∫ùóçùóÇùóàùóá\mathsf{initialization}sansserif_initialization phase as the graph index for accuracy improvement. As demonstrated in previous experimental studies (Li et¬†al., 2019; Wang et¬†al., 2021a), with similar (e.g. tens of ) average out-degrees, KNNG is more prone to local optima than RNG and NSWG due to directional edges and weak connectivity. To address this, RNG equips the initial KNNG with a pretty large (e.g. hundreds of) out-degree, which enhances the kùëòkitalic_k-CNA quality but leads to an inefficiency issue. As depicted in Figure¬†3(a), the search on KNNG to enhance the kùëòkitalic_k-CNA quality constitutes a significant portion of the overall cost of building the representative RNG method (i.e., NSG), which even surpasses that taken for ùóÇùóáùóÇùóçùóÇùñ∫ùóÖùóÇùóìùñ∫ùóçùóÇùóàùóáùóÇùóáùóÇùóçùóÇùñ∫ùóÖùóÇùóìùñ∫ùóçùóÇùóàùóá\mathsf{initialization}sansserif_initialization on the ùñ¶ùóÇùóåùóçùü£ùñ¨ùñ¶ùóÇùóåùóçùü£ùñ¨\mathsf{Gist1M}sansserif_Gist1M dataset. A similar phenomenon could be found in other RNG methods such as œÑùúè\tauitalic_œÑ-MNG.

NSWG Construction Issue: NSWG methods suffer from a poor kùëòkitalic_k-CNA quality in construction, caused by its building strategy of incremental node-by-node insertions: utilizes the current graph index with only a part of nodes to conduct kùëòkitalic_k-ANN search for kùëòkitalic_k-CNA results. Hence, the expected value of kùëòkitalic_k-CNA quality in NSWG is only 0.50.50.50.5 even if all the kùëòkitalic_k-ANN queries are answered correctly. Since achieving exact correctness in kùëòkitalic_k-ANN queries is not feasible, the average recall in practice is upper bounded by 0.50.50.50.5, as demonstrated in Figure¬†2(b).

4. Refinement Before Search

In this section, we focus on addressing the issue identified in the last section regarding the RNG construction. At a high level, we propose replacing the search-before-refinement scheme (Figure¬†1(a)) with a refinement-before-search scheme (Figure 1(c)) in RNG construction. To enhance the efficiency of acquiring high-quality kùëòkitalic_k-CNA results, we introduce a novel pruning strategy, Œ±ùõº\alphaitalic_Œ±-pruning for neighbor selection in ùóãùñæùñøùóÇùóáùñæùóÜùñæùóáùóçùóãùñæùñøùóÇùóáùñæùóÜùñæùóáùóç\mathsf{refinement}sansserif_refinement (Section¬†4.1). Then, we theoretically analyze our proposed scheme to demonstrate its efficacy (Section¬†4.2).

4.1. Œ±ùõº\alphaitalic_Œ±-Pruning Strategy

To enhance the kùëòkitalic_k-CNA efficiency in RNG, we do not use the initial KNNG Gùê∫Gitalic_G as the index used in ùóåùñæùñ∫ùóãùñºùóÅùóåùñæùñ∫ùóãùñºùóÅ\mathsf{search}sansserif_search phase due to its large out-degree. However, altering the order of ùóãùñæùñøùóÇùóáùñæùóÜùñæùóáùóçùóãùñæùñøùóÇùóáùñæùóÜùñæùóáùóç\mathsf{refinement}sansserif_refinement and ùóåùñæùñ∫ùóãùñºùóÅùóåùñæùñ∫ùóãùñºùóÅ\mathsf{search}sansserif_search directly is unsuitable for index construction due to the following issue.

5. A New PG Construction Framework

In this section, we provide comprehensive details of our new construction framework for RNG and NSWG. Combining the approaches outlined in the previous section, we begin by presenting an optimized kùëòkitalic_k-CNA approach in Section¬†5.1, and then we present our new construction methods for RNG on top of our optimized kùëòkitalic_k-CNA approach, as in Section¬†5.2. Further, we enhance the NSWG construction by combining a layer-by-layer insertion strategy with the RNG construction framework in Section¬†5.3. In Section¬†5.4, optimization techniques are introduced to enhance the efficiency of RNG construction framework. Lastly, we consolidate all the methods discussed and present a streamlined and effective framework that can be applied to the construction of other PG methods, as in Section¬†5.5.

5.2. Self-Iterative Construction of RNG

According to our refinement-before-search scheme, we could generate the final RNG index by applying another ùóãùñæùñøùóÇùóáùñæùóÜùñæùóáùóçùóãùñæùñøùóÇùóáùñæùóÜùñæùóáùóç\mathsf{refinement}sansserif_refinement on the results of OptKCNA. However, such a simple construction strategy still faces the following challenges, in order to balance the kùëòkitalic_k-CNA efficiency and quality.

Difficulty of Tuning Parameters in ùñ≤ùñæùñ∫ùóãùñºùóÅùñ≤ùñæùñ∫ùóãùñºùóÅ\mathsf{Search}sansserif_Search Phase: In the ùóåùñæùñ∫ùóãùñºùóÅùóåùñæùñ∫ùóãùñºùóÅ\mathsf{search}sansserif_search phase, LùêøLitalic_L is the key parameter to the efficiency-quality balance and thus should be carefully selected. However, the best choice of LùêøLitalic_L varies from datasets. Grid search is commonly employed for finding the best LùêøLitalic_L¬†(Wang et¬†al., 2021a; Li et¬†al., 2019), which builds a corresponding graph index for each potential LùêøLitalic_L value with a huge cost. Hence, this one-shot strategy of setting LùêøLitalic_L is considerably time-consuming.

To address this issue, we take the progressive strategy of tuning LùêøLitalic_L and propose a self-iterative framework with two key components, i.e., quality examination and iterative refinement. The former determines the termination condition of our framework, while the latter defines the behaviour in each iteration. Again, we use the NSG as the representative RNG to illustrate the details.

As mentioned in the previous section regarding the NSWG construction issue, the poor kùëòkitalic_k-CNA quality primarily arises due to the incremental node-by-node insertion strategy and the ùóåùñæùñ∫ùóãùñºùóÅùóåùñæùñ∫ùóãùñºùóÅ\mathsf{search}sansserif_search conducted on the current incomplete graph index that includes only a portion of nodes. In this part, we still use HNSW as the representative NSWG index, and propose a global construction of HNSW, which achieves kùëòkitalic_k-CNA results on whole data points in each layer instead of only a part.

Our global construction of HNSW is built on top of a layer-by-layer insertion strategy in a top-down manner. To be specific, we first determine the layers for each node before the actual layer insertion and thus we obtain the whole set of nodes in each layer. Afterward, we employ our RNG construction framework in Section¬†5.2 to build a graph index for each layer. In this way, each layer of HNSW is built on top of kùëòkitalic_k-CNA results w.r.t the whole set of nodes in each layer instead of only a subset. Hence, the kùëòkitalic_k-CNA quality of each layer will significantly exceed 0.5 (i.e., the upper bound in the original HNSW). Note that each layer of HNSW is actually an RNG index, since it takes the RNG pruning strategy to prune the kùëòkitalic_k-CNA results only without the connectivity enhancement via DFS. Subsequently, we insert the RNG index of the layer into HNSW according to the layer-by-layer insertion strategy.

The details of our HNSW construction are presented in Algorithm¬†7. Initially, we randomly determine the layer of each node, following the same approach as in the original HNSW (Lines 1-3). Then, we select one node at the top layer as the entry node e‚Å¢pùëíùëùepitalic_e italic_p (Line 4). The index construction proceeds from the top layer to the bottom layer (Line 5). For nodes in each layer (Line 6), we directly connect them if the number of nodes does not exceed the out-degree limit MùëÄMitalic_M (Lines 7-8). Alternatively, we apply our optimized NSG construction to obtain the index (Lines 9-10).

5.5. Summary

The pipeline of our framework is summarized in Figure¬†1(c). In the beginning, we obtain a KNNG through the ùóÇùóáùóÇùóçùóÇùñ∫ùóÖùóÇùóìùñ∫ùóçùóÇùóàùóáùóÇùóáùóÇùóçùóÇùñ∫ùóÖùóÇùóìùñ∫ùóçùóÇùóàùóá\mathsf{initialization}sansserif_initialization phase and then enter an iterative loop to continuously enhance the kùëòkitalic_k-CNA quality until it satisfies the quality examination or achieves the required number of iterations. During each iteration, we first obtain an intermediate graph index from the current kùëòkitalic_k-CNA results via a new pruning strategy for neighbor selection in the ùóãùñæùñøùóÇùóáùñæùóÜùñæùóáùóçùóãùñæùñøùóÇùóáùñæùóÜùñæùóáùóç\mathsf{refinement}sansserif_refinement phase. Subsequently, we perform a beam search for each node in the ùóåùñæùñ∫ùóãùñºùóÅùóåùñæùñ∫ùóãùñºùóÅ\mathsf{search}sansserif_search phase to enhance the kùëòkitalic_k-CNA quality. The optimization techniques, i.e., ùñ™ùü§ùñØùñ™ùü§ùñØ\mathsf{K2P}sansserif_K2P and ùñØùü§ùñ™ùñØùü§ùñ™\mathsf{P2K}sansserif_P2K, further accelerate the ùóãùñæùñøùóÇùóáùñæùóÜùñæùóáùóçùóãùñæùñøùóÇùóáùñæùóÜùñæùóáùóç\mathsf{refinement}sansserif_refinement and ùóåùñæùñ∫ùóãùñºùóÅùóåùñæùñ∫ùóãùñºùóÅ\mathsf{search}sansserif_search phases respectively.

It is important to note that our framework is not only well-suited for NSG and HNSW, as detailed in this section, but also could be extended to the construction of other SOTA PGs, such as œÑùúè\tauitalic_œÑ-MNG¬†(Peng et¬†al., 2023) and NSW¬†(Malkov et¬†al., 2014) (as demonstrated in Exp.5 in Section¬†6). This is due to the fact that the construction pipelines of all SOTA PGs fall into the two categories we have discussed.

6. Experiments

In this section, we present the results of our experimental study. We begin by introducing the experimental settings, followed by showcasing the building cost and search performance results when applying our framework to NSG, HNSW, œÑùúè\tauitalic_œÑ-MNG and NSW. Furthermore, we compare our framework with four up-to-date methods to highlight the enhanced efficiency of our index construction without compromising search performance. Lastly, we analyze the effects of the optimization techniques employed and demonstrate the scalability of our approach on a large dataset.

Datasets: We use 6 public datasets with diverse sizes and dimensions. These datasets encompass a wide range of applications, including image (Sift1M111http://corpus-texmex.irisa.fr/, ùñ£ùñæùñæùóâùü£ùñ¨ùñ£ùñæùñæùóâùü£ùñ¨\mathsf{Deep1M}sansserif_Deep1M 222https://disk.yandex.ru/d/11eDCm7Dsn9GA/ and Gist1M1), audio (Msong333http://www.ifs.tuwien.ac.at/mir/msd/) and text(Crawl444https://commoncrawl.org/ and ùñ¶ùóÖùóàùóèùñæùñ¶ùóÖùóàùóèùñæ\mathsf{Glove}sansserif_Glove 555https://nlp.stanford.edu/projects/glove/). The statistics of those data sets are summarised in Table 3, where #queries denotes the number of queries and dim. denotes the dimensions of datasets. The query workloads of the datasets are given in the datasets. Besides, we take several random samples of distinct sizes from Sift50M1 dataset to test the scalability of our methods.

Performance Indicators: Given a PG construction method, we care about two aspects of performance, i.e., construction cost and search performance. We use the execution time to evaluate the construction cost, denoted as ‚ÄúBuilding Time‚Äù. For search performance, we care about efficiency measured by queries per second (QPS) and accuracy evaluated by recall. Given a query qùëûqitalic_q, let kùëòkitalic_k denote the number of returned neighbors, N‚àó‚Å¢(q)superscriptùëÅùëûN^{*}(q)italic_N start_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ‚àó end_POSTSUPERSCRIPT ( italic_q ) be the exact kùëòkitalic_k-nearest neighbors of qùëûqitalic_q, while N‚Å¢(q)ùëÅùëûN(q)italic_N ( italic_q ) be the set of kùëòkitalic_k returned neighbors from different algorithms. Computing Environment: All experiments are conducted on a server equipped with 2 Intel(R) Xeon(R) Silver 4210R CPUs, each of which has 10 cores, and 256 GB DRAM as the main memory. The OS version is CentOS 7.9.2009. All codes were written by C++ and compiled by g++ 11.3. The SIMD instructions are enabled to accelerate the distance computations.

Exp.2 & 3: main experimental results in search performance & building time. In this part, we show the main results of this work by comparing our methods with the original algorithms in both search performance and building time. The comparison of search performance and building time are presented in Figures 10 and 12, respectively. First, we can find that FastNSG exhibits comparable search performance to OriNSG in Figure 10, while significantly reducing construction costs as shown in Figure 12. Specifically, FastNSG achieves speedups of 1.2x, 5.1x, 5.6x, 3.2x, 2.3x and 1.2x over OriNSG on the Sift1M, Gist1M, Msong, Crawl, Glove and Deep1M datasets, respectively. Second, FastHNSW demonstrates significantly improved search performance compared to OriHNSW, primarily due to obtaining more accurate kùëòkitalic_k-CNA results. Note that FastHNSW finds candidates for each point on the entire dataset in each layer, while OriHNSW only on a subset (the existing nodes in the graph during insertion). Compared with OriHNSW, FastHNSW accelerates construction by 2.4x, 4.6x, 3.0x, 3.7x, 1.6x and 2.1x speedups on the six datasets, respectively. In summary, our methods excel in construction efficiency while achieving comparable or even superior search performance.

7. Related Works

There have been a bulk of works on processing kùëòkitalic_k-ANN queries on high-dimensional data in the literature. To answer a kùëòkitalic_k-ANN query, index structures are widely used to carefully select a small part of high-quality candidates and then verify them via distance computations, in order to return accurate results with little cost. According to recent experimental studies (Aum√ºller et¬†al., 2020; Li et¬†al., 2020, 2019; Wang et¬†al., 2021a), proximity graphs (Fu et¬†al., 2019; Malkov and Yashunin, 2018; Fu et¬†al., 2022) outperform other index structures such as hashing-based methods (Datar et¬†al., 2004; Lv et¬†al., 2007; Liu et¬†al., 2014; Sun et¬†al., 2015), inverted index-based methods (Jegou et¬†al., 2011; Babenko and Lempitsky, 2014) and tree-based methods (Bentley, 1975; Muja and Lowe, 2014) in search performance. Due to their excellent search performance, the SOTA PG methods such as NSG (Fu et¬†al., 2019) and HNSW (Malkov and Yashunin, 2018) have been taken as the solution by industrial vector databases such as Milvus¬†(Wang et¬†al., 2021b) and VBase¬†(Zhang et¬†al., 2023).

Moreover, several works that combine the parallel power of GPU and the filtering capacity of PG methods have been proposed¬†(Zhao et¬†al., 2020; Groh et¬†al., 2022; Yu et¬†al., 2022; Ootomo et¬†al., 2023; Liu et¬†al., 2024a). SONG (Zhao et¬†al., 2020) modifies the search method of existing methods such as HNSW in order to achieve higher throughput. Other GPU-accelerated methods such as GGNN (Groh et¬†al., 2022), GANNS (Yu et¬†al., 2022) and CAGRA (Ootomo et¬†al., 2023) build their own graph index and have the corresponding search method. In addition, there exist I/O-efficient PG-based approaches, such as DiskANN (Subramanya et¬†al., 2019) and Starling (Wang et¬†al., 2024). Besides, some work expands kùëòkitalic_k-ANN search to various scenarios, such as hybrid search (Zhang et¬†al., 2023; Gollapudi et¬†al., 2023; Zuo et¬†al., 2024), out-of-distribution queries¬†(Jaiswal et¬†al., 2022), and search on billion-scale datasets¬†(Chen et¬†al., 2021; Jayaram¬†Subramanya et¬†al., 2019; Ni et¬†al., 2023).

8. Conclusion

In this paper, we study the efficient construction of the SOTA proximity graph-based approaches for kùëòkitalic_k-ANN search and start by revisiting existing PG construction approaches. We analyze the importance of kùëòkitalic_k-CNA quality on their construction efficiency and search performance, and figure out their issues on construction. To address these issues, we propose a novel construction framework for RNG with Œ±ùõº\alphaitalic_Œ±-pruning strategy and a self-iterative framework. We then combine the layer-by-layer insertion strategy with our RNG construction framework to address the construction issue of HNSW (i.e., the representative NSWG). Finally, we conduct extensive experiments on real-world datasets to showcase the superiority of our methods. The results show our approaches exhibit a construction speedup to 5.65.65.65.6x faster than the original methods of RNG and NSWG while delivering comparable or even superior search performance.
